│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ The root cause is that constraints from one branch of the dominator tree are leaking into  │
│ a sibling branch. When `eliminateConstraints` recursively processes the children of a      │
│ dominator tree node, it adds constraints specific to each child's subtree. After it's done │
│ with one child, it moves to the next, but it doesn't roll back the constraints added from  │
│ the previous child. The fix is to save the state of the `ConstraintSystem` before          │
│ iterating over the children and restore it afterward. This ensures that each sibling       │
│ subtree is analyzed with a clean slate of constraints, inheriting only from the common     │
│ parent.                                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ By adding `ConstraintSystem::SaveState OnExit(CS);` before the loop that iterates over the │
│ children of the current dominator tree node, we ensure that any modifications to the       │
│ `ConstraintSystem` `CS` within the loop (i.e., during the recursive calls to               │
│ `eliminateConstraints` for the children) are automatically undone when the `OnExit` object │
│ goes out of scope at the end of the current function's execution block. This correctly     │
│ isolates the constraints of sibling subtrees.                                              │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
│                                                                                            │
